<h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

<h3>How often should I get a massage?</h3>
<p>For general wellness and stress management, monthly massage is a good baseline. Active individuals, those managing chronic pain, or people in physically demanding jobs may benefit from bi-weekly sessions. During periods of high stress, injury recovery, or intensive training, weekly sessions may be appropriate. Discuss the optimal frequency with your therapist based on your specific situation and budget.</p>

<h3>Is massage covered by Spanish health insurance?</h3>
<p>Physiotherapy (which includes therapeutic massage) is often covered by private insurance (Sanitas, Asisa, Adeslas) when prescribed by a doctor or performed by a registered physiotherapist. Wellness or relaxation massage at spas is typically not covered. If you are receiving massage primarily for a medical condition (chronic pain, injury rehabilitation), ask your doctor for a physiotherapy referral to maximize insurance coverage.</p>

<h3>Can massage help with back pain?</h3>
<p>Yes. Massage is one of the most effective non-pharmaceutical treatments for back pain, as recognized by the American College of Physicians in their clinical practice guidelines. Deep tissue massage and myofascial release are particularly helpful for lower back pain. For chronic conditions, combining regular massage with exercise (particularly core strengthening) and ergonomic improvements yields the best long-term results.</p>

<h3>What is the difference between a massage therapist and a physiotherapist?</h3>
<p>In Spain, a physiotherapist (fisioterapeuta) holds a university degree (4-year Grado en Fisioterapia) and is a registered healthcare professional. They can diagnose musculoskeletal conditions, create rehabilitation programs, and use a wider range of techniques including ultrasound, electrotherapy, and dry needling. A massage therapist may hold various certifications but is not a registered healthcare professional. For therapeutic or medical massage needs, a physiotherapist is generally the better choice. For relaxation and general wellness, both can provide excellent service.</p>

<h3>Is it normal to feel sore after a massage?</h3>
<p>Mild soreness for 24 to 48 hours after deep tissue, sports, or myofascial release work is completely normal and is similar to post-exercise muscle soreness. It indicates that adhesions and tension have been worked on and the body is healing. If soreness persists beyond 48 hours, is severe, or involves bruising, the pressure was likely too intense — communicate this at your next session so the therapist can adjust. After a relaxation or Swedish massage, you should not feel sore.</p>

<h3>Can I get a massage if I have a sunburn?</h3>
<p>This is a particularly relevant question in Mallorca. Massage should be avoided on sunburned areas, as the pressure and friction can worsen the burn, cause pain, and potentially damage healing skin. If only a small area is burned, your therapist can work around it. If you have extensive sunburn, it is best to reschedule your massage until the burn has healed (typically 3 to 7 days for mild sunburn).</p>

